\section{The DNA sequencing, a typical micro-array application}
\label{sec:DNA_seq}
To appreciate the challenges of DNA sequencing a brief explanation on the basics of genetic and DNA is necessary.

\subsubsection{What is DNA?}
DNA also known as desoxyribonucleique acid is a biological macromolecule present in every living cells and in some viruses. DNA contains all the genetic information, called genotype, which ensure the development and the correct operations of living organisms.

The DNA molecule consists of two biopolymer strands known as polynucleotides. Each monomere constituting of the strands is called a nucleotide which is formed by a phosphate group of chemical composition \chemform{PO_4}, a monosaccharide sugar known as desoxyribose and a nitrogen-containing nucleobase. There are four different nucleotides denote by the name of their four different nucleobases: Adenine (A), Guanine (G), Cytosine (C) and Thymine (T).

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\subfigure[DNA double helix structure.]{\label{Fig:DNA_helix}\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{Figs/Chap1//DNA_helix.png}}
\subfigure[DNA chemical structure.]{\label{Fig:DNA_chem}\includegraphics[width=0.43\textwidth]{Figs/Chap1//DNA_chem.png}}
\caption{\footnotesize Representation of the DNA.}
\label{Fig:RepDNA}
\end{figure}

According to the model of J.D. Watson and F.H.C. Crick developed in 1953~\citep{RefWorks:150}, the two strands of nucleotides are tied together by hydrogen bonding's and formed an hybrid molecule shapes as a double helix. These two filaments present two major properties;
\begin{my_itemize}
\item Antiparallelism: the two strands are aligned in opposite directions to one another as shown in Fig.~\ref{Fig:DNA_helix}
\item Complementarity: each adenine of one strand is bound to a thymine of the other strand by two hydrogen bridges (A=T \& T=A) and each guanine of a strand is bound to a cytosine by three hydrogen bridges (C$\equiv$G \& G$\equiv$C).
\end{my_itemize}
Thus if we write in order, from the 3' end to the 5' end, the letters given on each strands of the Fig.~\ref{Fig:DNA_chem}, the following sequence is obtained;
\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{ l c c c c r }
  - - - & T & G & A & C & - - - \\
  - - - & A & C & T & A & - - - \\
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsubsection{What is the gene expression?}
The biosynthesis of a protein requires in the DNA structure a sequence of nucleotide which contains all the necessary information. This sequence is the gene of the protein as the string presented in Fig.~\ref{Fig:gene_seq}. Despite the fact that it is difficult to read, it contains all the information to synthesize a protein, in this case the Apolipoprotein A-II. The DNA strain containing the gene is called the ``sense'' strain whereas the other one is the ``antisense'' strain.~\citep{RefWorks:141}
\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[scale=0.25]{Figs/Chap1/gene_seq.png}
  \caption{\footnotesize Example of genetic sequence.}
  \label{Fig:gene_seq}
\end{figure}

The various mechanism set up to translate the information from a gene to the synthesis of a functional product is the gene expression. Then the genome is the whole genetic material of an organism encoded in his DNA.

Each cell division is preceded by a DNA replication leading to chromosome replication. This process normally retains the genetic information of the cell as long as each of the two daughter cells inherit a complete gene pool identical to the mother cell. Sometimes, this process is not operating normally and the cell's genetic information is modified. This permanent change of the nucleotide sequence of a gene is a genetic mutation.

\subsubsection{Why do we use DNA sequencing?}
Mutations or alterations of the genotype may either remain without any effects or can alter the gene expression or whether prevent the gene from working properly. Thus mutations produce discernible changes on the phenotype, \textit{i.e.} the observable characteristics of an organism. However, mutations are part in normal biological processes as evolution, development of the immune system and abnormal processes such as cancer or specific genetic disorders.~\citep{RefWorks:141}

In order to ``decode'' the instructions stored in a DNA molecule, the sequence of its bases must be determined. It is this ``reading'' of the sequence which is called DNA sequencing. As it is aforementioned, unlike reading a text, sequencing of DNA only delivers a long text of A, T, C and G in which the information are not immediately discernible. An interpretive step, called annotation is needed to identify the instructions and then understand the biological sense.

The genome and its operation is a crucial information about the well-functioning of a living organism. The creation of exhaustive inventory of the human genes is the main reason for sequencing programs. The understanding of genes is indeed a necessary step to perceive biological phenomena at the molecular and cellular level.

In the future, the applications of sequencing will be more and more numerous in the fields of medicine and pharmaceutical, biotechnology, food processing, as well as in other areas in direct contact with the biological processes (agriculture, environment). Such examples are the detection of Single Nucleotide Polymorphism (SNP), which allows to determine the reaction of a patient to a treatment, or the complete sequencing of the genome to prevent some cancers or genetic diseases. All the possible applications of DNA sequencing justifies the search for effective and affordable sequencing technologies.

\subsubsection{How to perform DNA sequencing?}
DNA sequencing was invented in the second half of the 1970s. Two methods have been developed independently by the team of Walter Gilbert in the United States and the team of Frederick Sanger in the UK. Both methods are based on opposite principles: Sanger approach is a method by selective enzymatic synthesis while that of Maxam and Gilbert is a method by selective chemical degradation.

Meanwhile, DNA micro-arrays also known as bio-chip or DNA chip were developed as an other approach to perform DNA sequencing with better throughput. As shown Fig.~\ref{Fig:DNA_micro} it is a set of DNA molecules fixed in ordered rows on a small area which may be glass, silicon or plastic. This recent biotechnology is used to analyze the genes into cells, tissues, organs, or complex mixtures, at a given time and in a given state with respect to a reference sample.
\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[scale=0.65]{Figs/Chap1//DNA_microarray.png}
  \caption{\footnotesize Basic operation principle of DNA microarrays.~\citep{RefWorks:151}}
  \label{Fig:DNA_micro}
\end{figure}

DAN micro-arrays are based on the property that a ``denatured'' DNA strand tends to spontaneously reform the double helix when presented to its complementary strand. Thus the DNA strands in the sample to analyze will bond to the complementary strands on the DNA chip, this is the hybridization reaction. For instance, if a patient has a disease, extracts of retro-transcribed DNA strand will hybridize with representative synthetic DNA strands of the disease. Then, the binding can be detected by different methods. Optical based methods use a fluorescent dye added to the DNA sample to detect hybridized pairs using a microscope. Some semiconductor based techniques use CMOS sensors or MEMS cantilevers to detect any bonding.

\subsubsection{What is CMOS microarray?}
As mentioned in the previous subsection some DNA microarrays are based on CMOS techniques. According to the Moore's scaling law the utilization of CMOS processes allows to integrate more and more sensors on a chip as well as decreasing the cost.~\citep{RefWorks:117} It differs from optical sequencing methods which required expensive and large components such as lenses and cameras. A commercially genetic sequencing system a sensing array is demonstrated in~\citep{RefWorks:128}.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\subfigure[Top view of the wells~\citep{RefWorks:151}]{\label{Fig:DNA_well_top}\includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{Figs/Chap1//DNA_well.png}}
\subfigure[Side view of the wells~\citep{RefWorks:128}]{\label{Fig:DNA_well_side}\includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth]{Figs/Chap1//DNA_well_2.png}}
\caption{\footnotesize Electron micrographs of micro-wells for DNA microarray.}
\label{Fig:DNA_well}
\end{figure}
Different technologies are used to perform DNA sequencing. This thesis focus on a technique known as ion semiconductor sequencing which uses specific CMOS sensors to detect a variation of pH due to hybridization. In any cases CMOS microarrays require multiple wells on top of sensors to contain the DNA sample to analyze as it is shown on Fig.~\ref{Fig:DNA_well}

CMOS-based microarrays open the way to high-throughput and high parallelism~\citep{RefWorks:110} for fast and cost-effective systems.

\subsubsection{High-throughput sequencing?}
High-Throughput Sequencing (HTS) also known as NGS for Next-Generation Sequencing refers to a set of methods that emerged from 2005 which produce millions of sequences in one run for a low cost. Pyrosequencing and novel hybridization methods belongs to these new techniques. They are characterized by the use of massive parallel approaches to sequence hundreds of thousands of fragments simultaneously.~\citep{RefWorks:120} They are freed of the cloning steps and formations of genomic libraries. They allow sequencing directly from single DNA molecules.

In this case nucleotides are not added together as in a normal sequencing reaction but one after the other (cf. Fig.~\ref{Fig:DNA_pyro}). If the nucleotide added to the reaction medium corresponds to the one expected by the polymerase (parent strand), it is incorporated into the growing strand (elongation) and releases chemical species such as a pyrophosphate \chemform{PP_i} and a proton \chemform{H+}, as presented in~\ref{Fig:DNA_hybrid}.
\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[scale=0.23]{Figs/Chap1//DNA_hybridization.png}
  \caption{\footnotesize Reaction of DNA hybridization.}
  \label{Fig:DNA_hybrid}
\end{figure}

For pH-sequencing a reaction leads to a drop in pH, the sequencer or more precisely a pH-sensor will detect the chemical evolution of protons in solution signal and produce the form of a peak on the output signal. The height of this peak is a function of the pH-intensity signal itself proportional to the number of nucleotides incorporated at the same time. (Fig.~\ref{Fig:DNA_seq}) The gene sequence is deduced from the size of the peaks obtained. Moreover, in case of mixture of nucleotides at the same position (sequence polymorphism), the size of the peaks provides a quantification of the proportion of nucleotides present on the growing strand.
\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\subfigure[Parallel sequencing method~\citep{RefWorks:116}]{\label{Fig:DNA_pyro}\includegraphics[width=0.35\textwidth]{Figs/Chap1//DNA_seq.png}}
\subfigure[Result of nucleotide detection~\citep{RefWorks:120}]{\label{Fig:DNA_seq}\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{Figs/Chap1//DNA_pyroseq.png}}
\caption{\footnotesize Presentation of high-throughput sequencing methods.}
\label{Fig:HTS}
\end{figure}

