\section{The honeycomb}
\label{sec:Honeycomb}

In the Section~\ref{sec:DNA_seq} we have seen the interest of DNA micro-arrays and the organization of the sensing wells. As a consequence designers need to find the best solution to arrange the wells and obtain the most compact structure.

Moreover, in Mathematics, any area covered completely by identical plane shapes without overlapping and regardless of their design (regular convex, irregular and concave, with straight or curved edges) is called a tiling. In this way, for the well of our micro-array, we need to find the best shape yet all shapes such as squares, rectangles, hexagons, triangles or even Escher's tiling are possible. The only constraint is on the area of the shapes; each shapes must have the same surface.

\textit{Which shape should be selected?}
One point that would be interesting would be minimizing the amount of material necessary to create the sides of the wells. Then, the shape with the smallest perimeter should be used.

\textit{But which geometric shape for a given surface has the smallest perimeter?}
The response has long been known: it is the disc. Yet, discs can not make a compact tiling, so a geometric shape that has the smallest perimeter and allow to cover completely an area has to be used.

\subsubsection{The honeycomb conjecture}
The answer to the problem presented previously is known since the Greek Antiquity. The solution is to use regular hexagons. However, even though the answer is admitted for more than two thousand years, nobody managed to give a proper demonstration of this solution. This is only in 1999 that the mathematician Thomas Hale provided a rigorous proof of this result.~\citep{RefWorks:61}

The honeycomb conjecture states that the regular hexagonal grid or honeycomb divides a surface into regions of equal area with the least total perimeter, this is the optimum tiling.

\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[scale=0.5]{Figs/Chap1//honeycomb.jpg}
  \footnotesize \textit{``[The honeycomb is] absolutely perfect in economizing labor and wax.''\\
 Charles Darwin}
  \label{Fig:ISFET_noise}
\end{figure}
Nature is well designed, so it is not a surprise that the utilization of hexagonal structures is found among the animal and plant kingdoms, including the well-known example of cells of the honeycombs created by the bees. As the hexagon minimizes the amount of material used to build the walls, it can diminish the amount of wax used to create the cavities. The fact that bees use the hexagonal tiling as the best tilling gave its name to the honeycomb conjecture.

The industry was largely inspired by honeycombs and now offers cellular structures that offer an amazing strength for a reduced cost since 95\% of these structures is composed of vacuum. The honeycomb structures serve to strengthen the resistance of a component while ensuring maximum lightness. The honeycomb may be made of aluminum, paper, cardboard or synthetic plastics material.

\subsubsection{Packing of equal spheres}
The hexagonal tilling and honeycomb is also related to the densest packing of equal circle in a plane. More generally, the dense sphere packing refers to the question: how to arrange spheres in the space in order to have the greatest density without overlapping?

This is a problem which arises in general Euclidean geometry in three-dimensional space, but which can also be generalized to the Euclidean plane (the spheres are replaced by circles), in a Euclidean space of $n$ dimensions $(n > 3)$, with hyper-spheres, or in a non-Euclidean space.

\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[scale=1]{Figs/Chap1//circle_packing.png}
  \caption{\footnotesize Dense circle packing in a square space.}
  \label{Fig:circle_pack}
\end{figure}
As shown in Fig.~\ref{Fig:circle_pack} the hexagonal shape is the most compact organization when we arrange circles of the same area in an appropriately sized enclosure. Carl Friedrich Gauss proved that no other regular patterns is denser. It is not the case when the spheres do not have the same size.

The surface density of this arrangement is;
\begin{equation}
    d = \frac{\pi}{2 \sqrt{3}} \simeq 0.9069
\label{density_hex}
\end{equation}
Every circle is tangent to 6 other circles which fill just over 90\% of the area of the plane.

\subsubsection{Conclusions}
Compactness matters. The more compact your structure, the more you can place wells on the DNA micro-array allowing HTS sequencing. The hexagonal tilling is the most effective %effective what ? choice ?%, superior to any non-convex and any paving comprising one or more curved sides.

In the next step of this work, we are going to analyze this hexagonal shape and see the possible application to the transistor geometry as well as the pros and the cons of such architecture.

