\section{High speed, small area and good matching applications}
\label{sec:HEX_app}
In Section~\ref{sec:pH_ISFET}, the ISFET model is presented as a MOSFET transistor with the gate as a reference electrode and an insulating layer sensitive to pH.

However, since the first transistor's realization in 1947, physicists and electronic engineers are looking to improve the performance of the device. This section presents a new architecture of MOSFET based on Enclosed Gate Transistors (EGTs) and their principle applications. The details on the electronic model and the performances of EGTs will be provided in Chapter~\ref{chap:LiteratureReview}.

\subsubsection{Enclosed Gate Transistors}
Enclosed Gate Transistors refer to non-conventional transistors with respect to common rectangular gate transistors (RGTs), and regroup different geometries such as the Circular Gate Transistor (CGT), the closed with $n$ sides, the donut or doughnut, the square, and the hexagonal transistors. Two types of EGTs are presented in Fig.~\ref{Fig:EGT}, it can be noticed that in all cases the gate should ``enclosed'' around the source or drain.
\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\subfigure[Square-shape MOS transistor~\citep{RefWorks:145}]{\label{Fig:EGT_sqr}\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{Figs/Chap1//EGT_sqr.png}}
\subfigure[Octagon-shape MOS transistor~\citep{RefWorks:57}]{\label{Fig:EGT_oct}\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{Figs/Chap1//EGT_oct.png}}
\caption{\footnotesize Schematics layout of Enclosed Gate Transistor}
\label{Fig:EGT}
\end{figure}
The utilization of EGTs is more and more incorporated into new designs of integrated circuits and the various patents developed demonstrate the interest of designers to such structures. Different typologies can be found such as hexagonal structures~\citep{RefWorks:131, RefWorks:132, RefWorks:133}, CGTs~\citep{RefWorks:134} and doughnut transistors~\citep{RefWorks:62} or even non-regular geometry~\citep{RefWorks:135}.

The first application discovered for EGTs was for power systems. In~\citep{RefWorks:44}, an example of the researches for POWER devices which use EGTs is developed. For power-MOS devices, the idea is to reduce the on-resistance, increasing the breakdown voltage and the reliability. Different layout geometry designs affect the parameters of the device. It includes on-resistance, breakdown voltage and threshold voltage.

\subsubsection{High-speed application}
EGTs present properties such as minimized stray capacitances associated with drain-substrate junctions which appears particularly useful in high-frequency application. In various papers, compact architectures of EGTs are presented. They present more effective rapports between current-driving strength and active area. They %also% obtained results concerning parameters such as capacitance %to% indicate a reduction in source/drain capacitance depending of the type of EGTs chosen.~\citep{RefWorks:57}

As a consequence EGTs are used as amplifiers or phase-lock loops. For instance,~\citep{RefWorks:53} presents a compact layout scheme of EGT to fabricate a high-speed mixed-signal circuit and RF circuits. Thanks to the properties of the EGTs the results obtained show an improvement of more than ``10\% of propagation delay of buffer circuits and an increase in the unity-gain frequency and phase margin of a high-speed two-stage operational amplifier''. Using EGTs, they %they faire référence à quoi ?% are even going further by creating an active compact inductor with Q value and saving space on the final design. In this case a waffle architecture is used, which consists of multiple EGTs.
Digital high speed applications have also been tested. In~\citep{RefWorks:45} a doughnut layout style is used for CMOS logic gates to improve switching speed %. It is compared to standard ... ?% and compared with standard layout style as shown in Fig.~\ref{EGT_digital}.

\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[scale=0.5]{Figs/Chap1//EGT_digital.png}
  \caption{\footnotesize Implementation of EGT logic gates, NOR(left) and NAND(right)~\citep{RefWorks:45}}
  \label{Fig:EGT_digital}
\end{figure}

These gates using the doughnut style are then used for the design of a fast 30-bit incrementer. The results obtained %results are ou result is ?% a maximum propagation delay of 10ns for a 3$\mu$m process. Unfortunately, no results are given for the same structure using RGTs, yet, it demonstrates an example of application in digital for EGTs.

The last but not least applications which are close to high-speed applications are space electronics utilization's. Indeed, EGT presents an improved radiation hardness due to ``the reduction of radiation-induced oxide trapped charge characteristic of deep-submicron processes''~\citep{RefWorks:63}. The fabrication of radiation tolerant devices is relatively recent but the application in high-energy physic domains such as in space or in particle accelerator~\citep{RefWorks:82} are multiples.

\subsubsection{High-density layout style with good matching}
Although some EGTs, such as CGTs are restricted as building components in general designing, they can be used in advantageous ways in large multicell arrays. Some topologies can even be inserted in CMOS chip without any extra processing work or cost. This is especially the case with waffle (Fig. \label{Fig:EGT_waffle}) and hexagonal structures (Fig. \label{Fig:EGT_hex}).
\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\subfigure[Compact waffle MOSFET design~\citep{RefWorks:145}]{\label{Fig:EGT_waffle}\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{Figs/Chap1//EGT_waffle.png}}
\subfigure[Compact hexagonal MOSFET structure~\citep{RefWorks:51}]{\label{Fig:EGT_hex}\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{Figs/Chap1//EGT_hex.png}}
\caption{\footnotesize Example of two compact ECG designs}
\label{Fig:EGT_compact}
\end{figure}

We have seen that the hexagonal tilling is the densest way to arrange circles in two dimensions, then the high density of hexagonal structure is easily proven. It could also be noticed that it helps to improve the matching of the transistor, which is true for all EGT structures. The Fig.~\ref{} presents the standard deviation on the mismatch of the voltage threshold $V_{TH}$ obtain%ed% for different layout styles and different sizes.
\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[scale=0.3]{Figs/Chap1//EGT_matching.png}
  \caption{\footnotesize Evolution of $V_{TH}$ mismatch for different layout style~\citep{RefWorks:48}}
  \label{Fig:EGT_matching}
\end{figure}

According to this result this type of EGT structure (here the waffle) avoids systematic mismatching to follow the linear relationship with the inverse of the transistor channel area. Other sources such as~\citep{RefWorks:51} present the same advantages this time for hexagonal EGT%s% instead of waffle structures.

Finally, application of high-density layouts and CMOS technology of the previously described honeycomb structure (\textit{cf}. Section~\ref{sec:Honeycomb}) are also part of EGT structures. Automatic packing algorithms for non-Manhattan hexagon placements are presented in~\citep{RefWorks:85} and~\citep{RefWorks:86} %. They take advantage of % hexagon honeycomb in new layout organization of cells. However, even though this implementation and algorithm demonstrate a better usage of the chip area, they are still not in use.

\subsubsection{Conclusions}
This section is a summary about the development and the main area of researches for EGT and especially hexagonal ISFETs. Their known advantages are; diminution of stray capacitance, better matching, hardness to radiation and better integration.

